    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism argues that the meaning of a law should be determined by how the text was understood at the time it was enacted. Proponents believe this keeps government within the bounds intended by the founders, preventing judicial overreach or changing the Constitution's meaning based on modern societal values. It focuses on the original public understanding or the intent of the framers as the authoritative source of law. Ultimately, the logic is that law should be static and faithful to its origins rather than evolving with current political preferences.",
