    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so i've been reading some stuff online and a lot of people say that originalism is basically just a way for judges to push their own political agendas by pretending they're just following old text. do they actually have a rebuttal for that, or is it mostly just a cover for conservative rulings?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Supporters of originalism strongly rebut this charge by arguing that their aim is objective interpretation, not subjective advocacy. They contend that adhering to an original public meaning *is* a consistent methodology, which prevents judges from inserting personal biases into constitutional interpretation. They see their adherence to historical texts as a commitment to limiting judicial power, whereas opponents view it as merely a convenient disguise for desired political outcomes.",
      "source": "target",
